We use the daily, 2.5°-regridded NOAA Optimum Interpolation SST V2 

Reynolds et al., 2007 avialable on the Pythia Jetstream2 S3 bucket as a Zarr store. The full record runs from September 1981 to the present and covers the tropics from 30°S to 30°N. The cell below opens the store lazily, no data are actually transferred until we compute something.

sst_noaa_oi_store = s3fs.S3Map(
    root="pythia/sst_noaa_oi.zarr",
    s3=fs,
    check=False,
)

sst_noaa_oi = xr.open_zarr(sst_noaa_oi_store)

if "__xarray_dataarray_variable__" in sst_noaa_oi.data_vars:
    sst_noaa_oi = sst_noaa_oi.rename_vars(
        {"__xarray_dataarray_variable__": "sst"}
    )

sst_noaa_oi

Two covariance matrices can be formed from the same data matrix:\mathbf{C}_{\text{time}} = \mathbf{X}^{\mathsf T}\mathbf{X}
\qquad (n_t \times n_t)\mathbf{C}_{\text{space}} = \mathbf{X}\mathbf{X}^{\mathsf T}
\qquad (m \times m)

\mathbf{C}_{\text{time}} captures temporal co-variability (each entry compares two time indices across all spatial points).

\mathbf{C}_{\text{space}} captures spatial co-variability (each entry compares two spatial locations across all times).

In practice we diagonalize the smaller matrix for computational efficiency.
